@incollection{Cottrell2002-dh,
	abstract = {Publisher Summary This chapter presents a brief
                 overview of work hardening. The turbulent flow of
                 fluids is the most difficult remaining problem in
                 classical physics. Work hardening is worse. The great
                 complicating feature of fluid flow---the presence of
                 non-linear inertial energy terms in the basic
                 equations---is ordinarily absent from work hardening. A
                 crucial assumption in all standard theories of plastic
                 deformation is that, dislocations move
                 ``non-relativistically,'' implying that when
                 accelerating among separate obstacles they do not
                 accumulate and store enough kinetic energy to help them
                 significantly in overcoming these obstacles. In other
                 words, the entire theory is quasi-static. If there were
