                 electrical resistance measurements can be informative
                 about the crack onset strain of brittle layers, such as
                 transparent conductors, or the stretchability of metal
                 interconnects. The combination of in situ electrical
                 measurements with in situ X-ray or confocal laser
                 scanning microscopy can provide even more information
                 about the failure mechanisms of the material systems.
                 Lattice strains and stresses can be measured with
                 X-rays, while cracking and buckle delaminations can be
                 studied with confocal laser scanning microscopy. These
                 new combinations of in situ methods will be discussed
