                 to a first-order nonequilibrium phase transition. As
                 the degree of annealing decreases, the first-order
                 character becomes weaker and the transition terminates
                 in a second-order critical point in the universality
                 class of an Ising model in a random field. For even
                 more poorly annealed systems, yielding becomes a smooth
                 crossover, representative of the ductile rheological
                 behavior generically observed in foams, emulsions, and
                 colloidal glasses. Our results show that the variety of
